    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "the counter idea makes sense, but i'm mostly worried about the edge cases. what if the leak isn't in the main loop itself, but some deep nested function call or a side effect of one of the sensor drivers? \n\nit feels like the memory just... disappears. one second we're fine, and then hours later the heap is just exhausted. how can i prove it's a specific subset of data causing it versus just a general failure to deallocate everything?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To prove the leak isn't random but tied to specific data, try injecting a unique \"tag\" into every `DataLog` object within your telemetry loop and track these tags in a global map. If a specific sensor ID or packet structure consistently generates tags that never appear in your cleanup logs, you've isolated the culprit to that data subset.\n\nYou can also create a mock \"stressed\" sensor that repeatedly sends the problematic payload directly into your `process_sensor_data` function during development to replicate the hours-long cycle without waiting for real-world drive time. This isolates the variable and forces the issue into a repeatable test case, allowing you to correlate the leak directly with the specific sensor driver or data format.\n\nSince you can't use Valgrind, you might consider implementing a simple heap tracker using `std::set` to record every allocation's address and a matching deallocation list, checking if any addresses remain after the \"steady state\" period. If you see addresses in the set that shouldn't be there, you'll have a concrete list of leaked pointers to trace back to their source code location.",
      "source": "target",
